signatures.description: The executable uses a known packer

T1045.long: Software packing is a method of compressing or encrypting an executable. Packing an executable changes the file signature in an attempt to avoid signature-based detection. Most decompression techniques decompress the executable code in memory.

strings: !This program cannot be run in DOS mode.
With no FILE, or when FILE is -, read standard input.
-b, --binary            read files in binary mode (default on DOS/Windows)
-c, --check             check MD5 sums against given list
The following two options are useful only when verifying checksums:
--status            don't output anything, status code shows success
-w, --warn              warn about improperly formated MD5 checksum lines
The sums are computed as described in RFC 1321.  When checking, the input
should be a former output of this program.  The default mode is to print
a line with checksum, a character indicating type (`*' for binary, ` ' for
text), and name for each FILE.
%s: no properly formatted MD5 checksum lines found
WARNING: %d of %d listed %s could not be read
WARNING: %d of %d computed %s did NOT match
the --binary and --text options are meaningless when verifying checksums
the --string and --check options are mutually exclusive
the --status option is meaningful only when verifying checksums
the --warn option is meaningful only when verifying checksums
no files may be specified when using --string
only one argument may be specified when using --check
